{
  "Overview of Cellular Respiration": "",
  "This lesson covers the fundamental measures of center used to analyze and summarize data sets. You'll learn how to calculate and apply the mean, median, and mode, and understand when each is most appropriate.": "",
  "What is the structure of the cell membrane according to the fluid mosaic model?": "",
  "Cell membrane — fluid mosaic model: (1) Phospholipid bilayer: each phospholipid has a hydrophilic head (phosphate group + glycerol) and two hydrophobic fatty acid tails → spontaneously forms bilayer in aqueous environment. ~5 nm thick. (2) 'Fluid': lipids and proteins move laterally within the bilayer (lateral diffusion: ~2 μm/sec for lipids). Flip-flop (transverse movement) is rare without flippase enzymes. (3) 'Mosaic': diverse proteins scattered through the membrane. Integral/transmembrane proteins: span entire bilayer (channels, carriers, receptors). Peripheral proteins: attached to surface (enzymes, cytoskeletal anchors). (4) Cholesterol: ~20% of animal cell membrane lipids. Wedges between phospholipids — at high temperature reduces fluidity (restricts movement); at low temperature prevents solidification (disrupts packing). Absent in most prokaryotes. (5) Glycocalyx: carbohydrate chains on glycoproteins and glycolipids (extracellular surface) — cell recognition, protection, cell-cell adhesion. Blood type antigens (A, B, O) are glycolipids/glycoproteins. (6) Selective permeability: small nonpolar molecules (O₂, CO₂, N₂) pass freely; small polar molecules (H₂O, ethanol) pass slowly; ions and large molecules require transport proteins.": "",
  "What is the structure and function of the nucleus in eukaryotic cells?": "",
  "The nucleus — command center of the cell: (1) Nuclear envelope: double membrane (outer continuous with rough ER). Nuclear pores (~3,000-4,000 per nucleus): large protein complexes (nucleoporins, ~120 MDa) that regulate bidirectional transport — small molecules diffuse freely; large molecules (proteins, RNA) require nuclear localization signals (NLS) and importin/exportin proteins (Ran-GTP cycle). (2) Chromatin: DNA + histone proteins. Euchromatin (loosely packed, transcriptionally active) vs. heterochromatin (tightly packed, mostly inactive). During cell division: chromatin condenses into visible chromosomes. Humans: 46 chromosomes (23 pairs). (3) Nucleolus: dense region within nucleus (not membrane-bound). Site of rRNA transcription (by RNA Pol I) and ribosome subunit assembly. rRNA genes are clustered on chromosomes 13, 14, 15, 21, 22 in humans (nucleolar organizer regions). Can have 1-4 nucleoli per nucleus. (4) Nuclear lamina: meshwork of intermediate filaments (lamins A, B, C) lining inner nuclear membrane — provides structural support, anchors chromatin, involved in DNA replication. Mutations in lamin A → progeria (Hutchinson-Gilford syndrome: premature aging). (5) Functions: DNA storage/protection, transcription (DNA → mRNA), RNA processing (splicing, capping, polyadenylation), ribosome assembly, cell cycle regulation.": "",
  "What is the function of the Golgi apparatus, and how does it process and sort proteins?": "",
  "Golgi apparatus — the cell's processing and shipping center: (1) Structure: stack of flattened membrane-bound sacs (cisternae), typically 4-8 per stack. Polarized: cis face (receiving side, near ER) → medial cisternae → trans face (shipping side, near plasma membrane). Trans-Golgi network (TGN): sorting station. (2) Receiving: COPII-coated vesicles bud from ER → fuse with cis-Golgi. (3) Modification: further glycosylation (N-linked oligosaccharides trimmed and modified; O-linked glycosylation added); phosphorylation; sulfation; proteolytic cleavage (e.g., proinsulin → insulin + C-peptide). (4) Sorting: mannose-6-phosphate (M6P) tag → M6P receptor → lysosomal delivery. Signal sequences on proteins determine routing. (5) Packaging and export: constitutive secretion (default pathway — continuous vesicle fusion with plasma membrane), regulated secretion (vesicles stored, released on signal — e.g., neurotransmitters, hormones), retrograde transport (COPI vesicles: Golgi → ER, retrieves escaped ER-resident proteins with KDEL signal). (6) Camillo Golgi discovered the apparatus in 1898 using silver nitrate staining of Purkinje neurons — shared Nobel Prize 1906 with Santiago Ramón y Cajal. (7) Clinical: I-cell disease (mucolipidosis II) — deficiency of GlcNAc phosphotransferase → proteins lack M6P tag → lysosomal enzymes secreted instead of delivered to lysosomes → cellular waste accumulates.": "",
  "A pathologist examining a liver biopsy from a patient with chronic alcohol abuse notices that the smooth endoplasmic reticulum (SER) in hepatocytes is dramatically enlarged — nearly three times the normal amount. The patient also reports needing higher doses of prescription medications to achieve the same effect. Using your knowledge of cell organelles, explain the connection between alcohol consumption, SER proliferation, and drug tolerance.": "",
  "SER proliferation and drug tolerance: (1) SER detoxification function: liver hepatocytes contain abundant SER with cytochrome P450 (CYP) enzymes — a superfamily of monooxygenases. CYP2E1 primarily metabolizes ethanol (also acetaminophen, anesthetics). CYP3A4 metabolizes ~50% of all prescription drugs. CYP2D6 metabolizes ~25% of drugs. (2) Enzyme induction: chronic alcohol exposure → gene upregulation → increased CYP enzyme synthesis → SER membrane proliferation to accommodate more enzymes. SER surface area can increase 2-3× in chronic alcoholics. (3) Cross-tolerance mechanism: more CYP enzymes → faster metabolism of ALL CYP substrates (not just alcohol) → drugs cleared faster → lower blood levels → reduced therapeutic effect → need higher doses. Clinically significant: alcoholics may need higher doses of anesthetics, sedatives, antidepressants, anticoagulants. (4) Dangerous interaction: acetaminophen (Tylenol) is metabolized by CYP2E1 to toxic NAPQI (normally detoxified by glutathione). Induced CYP2E1 in alcoholics → more NAPQI production + alcohol depletes glutathione → NAPQI accumulates → severe hepatotoxicity. Acetaminophen overdose + alcohol = leading cause of acute liver failure. (5) This demonstrates a fundamental cell biology principle: organelle quantity adapts to functional demand (organelle biogenesis is regulated).": "",
  "A child is diagnosed with Tay-Sachs disease after developing progressive neurological deterioration at 6 months of age. Genetic testing confirms a mutation in the HEXA gene encoding the lysosomal enzyme hexosaminidase A. Explain how this single enzyme deficiency leads to the devastating symptoms, and what this tells us about lysosomal function.": "",
  "Tay-Sachs disease — lysosomal storage disease paradigm: (1) Genetics: autosomal recessive. HEXA gene (chromosome 15) encodes α-subunit of hexosaminidase A (a heterodimer: α + β subunits). Carrier frequency: ~1/30 in Ashkenazi Jewish, French-Canadian, and Cajun populations (historical founder effects + possible heterozygote advantage against tuberculosis). (2) Biochemistry: hexosaminidase A normally cleaves terminal N-acetylgalactosamine from GM2 ganglioside in lysosomes → GM2 → GM3 → further degradation. Without functional enzyme → GM2 ganglioside accumulates. (3) Why neurons? Gangliosides are especially abundant in neuronal membranes (constitute ~6% of brain lipids). High ganglioside turnover → rapid accumulation of undegraded GM2. Lysosomes swell with membranous cytoplasmic bodies (MCBs) → physical distortion of neuronal architecture → axonal dysfunction → neuronal death. (4) Clinical: infantile form (most severe, >90% of cases): normal at birth; developmental regression at ~6 months; cherry-red spot on retinal exam (fovea appears red because surrounding ganglion cells are swollen/pale with lipid); progressive blindness, deafness, seizures; death by age 4-5. No cure; enzyme replacement therapy doesn't cross blood-brain barrier effectively. (5) Lesson: demonstrates lysosomal enzyme specificity — each of ~50 hydrolases has unique substrate(s), and deficiency of any one enzyme causes specific substrate accumulation → specific disease. Also illustrates: organelle dysfunction → cell dysfunction → tissue dysfunction → organismal disease.": "",
  "A microbiologist isolates a mysterious single-celled organism from a deep-sea hydrothermal vent. Initial examination shows it is 0.8 μm in diameter, has no visible nucleus, and can survive at 110°C. However, further analysis reveals that its membrane contains ether-linked lipids and it has histone-like proteins bound to its circular DNA. How would you classify this organism, and why doesn't it fit neatly into the 'prokaryote' category as traditionally understood?": "",
  "Archaea and the three domains: (1) Carl Woese (1977) used 16S rRNA sequencing to discover that 'prokaryotes' are actually two fundamentally different groups: Bacteria and Archaea. Led to the three-domain system (1990): Bacteria, Archaea, Eukarya. (2) Archaea — prokaryotic structure: no nuclear membrane, no membrane-bound organelles, small size (0.1-15 μm), circular chromosome(s), binary fission. BUT molecular features are a mosaic of bacterial AND eukaryotic traits. (3) Archaeal features shared with eukaryotes (not bacteria): histone-like proteins (archaeal histones wrap DNA similarly to eukaryotic nucleosomes), RNA polymerase similar to eukaryotic RNA Pol II (multi-subunit), TATA-binding protein (TBP) in transcription initiation, translation initiation with methionine (not formyl-methionine as in bacteria), some introns in tRNA genes. (4) Unique archaeal features: ether-linked lipids (isoprenoid chains linked to glycerol via ether bonds, vs. ester bonds in bacteria/eukaryotes → more heat-stable), some form lipid monolayers (tetraether lipids spanning entire membrane — extremely stable at high temperatures), unique cell wall composition (no peptidoglycan — pseudopeptidoglycan, S-layer, or none). (5) Extremophile archaea: thermophiles (Pyrolobus fumarii — up to 113°C), halophiles (Halobacterium — 5M NaCl), acidophiles (Sulfolobus — pH 1-2), methanogens (Methanobacterium — strict anaerobes, produce CH₄). But archaea also live in 'normal' environments — abundant in ocean water, soil, human gut. (6) Phylogenetic implication: Archaea + Eukaryota form a clade to the exclusion of Bacteria. Eukaryotes likely evolved from an archaeal ancestor (Asgard archaea — Lokiarchaeota discovered 2015 — closest known archaeal relatives of eukaryotes).": "",
  "A patient with primary ciliary dyskinesia (PCD, also called Kartagener syndrome when accompanied by situs inversus) suffers from chronic respiratory infections, infertility, and has a 50% chance of having mirror-reversed organ placement. His physician explains that all these symptoms result from defective cilia. How can one structural defect — in a cytoskeletal component — cause such diverse symptoms across different organ systems?": "",
  "Primary ciliary dyskinesia — one cytoskeletal defect, many organ systems: (1) Motile cilia structure: 9+2 axoneme (9 outer doublet microtubules + 2 central singlets). Outer and inner dynein arms (molecular motors) on outer doublets generate sliding force → bending. Nexin links and radial spokes coordinate bending → rhythmic beating pattern (~10-20 Hz). (2) PCD genetics: autosomal recessive. ~50 genes known. Most common: DNAI1, DNAH5 (outer dynein arm components). ~1/15,000-20,000 births. (3) Respiratory consequences: airway cilia (in trachea, bronchi — mucociliary escalator) beat in coordinated waves to move mucus + trapped particles upward toward pharynx → clearance. Defective cilia → mucus stagnation → bacterial colonization → chronic sinusitis, bronchitis, bronchiectasis (permanent airway dilation), otitis media. (4) Fertility: sperm flagellum has 9+2 axoneme (same dynein motors) → immotile sperm → male infertility. Fallopian tube cilia move ovum → female subfertility. (5) Situs inversus (Kartagener syndrome, ~50% of PCD): during embryonic development (day 7-8), nodal cilia at the embryonic node rotate clockwise → create leftward fluid flow → asymmetric gene expression (Nodal, Lefty, Pitx2) → normal left-right organ placement (situs solitus). Immotile nodal cilia → no directional flow → organ placement is random (50:50 normal or mirror-image). Most situs inversus patients are clinically normal (mirror-image organs work fine) unless accompanied by cardiac defects (heterotaxy). (6) Demonstrates: the cytoskeleton isn't just structural — microtubule-based motility is essential for mucus clearance, reproduction, and embryonic development.": "",
  "An immunologist explains to medical students how macrophages destroy bacteria using an elegant coordination of multiple organelles. A macrophage engulfs a Staphylococcus aureus bacterium. Trace the subsequent events, identifying each organelle involved and its role in the process.": "",
  "Phagocytosis — organelle coordination in immune defense: (1) Recognition: macrophage receptors (Toll-like receptors/TLRs, Fc receptors, complement receptors, mannose receptors) bind PAMPs on bacterial surface or opsonins (antibodies, complement C3b). (2) Engulfment: actin polymerization (cytoskeleton) drives pseudopod extension → bacterium enclosed in phagosome (membrane-bound vacuole derived from plasma membrane). Energy: mitochondrial ATP powers actin dynamics and membrane remodeling. (3) Phagosome maturation: early phagosome (Rab5 GTPase, slight acidification) → late phagosome (Rab7, more acidification by V-ATPase) → phagolysosomе (fusion with lysosome). Fusion mediated by SNARE proteins, Rab GTPases. (4) Killing and digestion in phagolysosome: pH drops to ~4.5 (V-ATPase proton pumps). Acid hydrolases: cathepsins (proteases), lysozyme (cleaves peptidoglycan), DNase/RNase, lipases, glycosidases. Oxidative burst: NADPH oxidase → superoxide (O₂⁻•) → H₂O₂ → HOCl (myeloperoxidase) — extremely bactericidal. iNOS → nitric oxide (NO•) → peroxynitrite (ONOO⁻). (5) Antigen presentation: bacterial protein fragments (peptides, 13-25 amino acids) loaded onto MHC class II molecules (assembled in ER, processed in Golgi) → transported to cell surface → presented to CD4⁺ helper T cells → adaptive immune response initiation. ER and Golgi are essential for MHC synthesis and processing. (6) Waste disposal: indigested remnants expelled by exocytosis. (7) Summary of organelles: cell membrane (recognition/engulfment), cytoskeleton-actin (pseudopodia), lysosomes (digestion), mitochondria (ATP), ER (MHC/protein synthesis), Golgi (MHC processing/lysosomal enzyme delivery), endosomes (maturation pathway).": ""
}